{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583650"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:22:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:22:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.06,0.54,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50387"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35616"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50387"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic to review results from a recent set of laboratory tests and investigations he had following an Emergency Department admission for haematemesis. He has a history of heavy alcohol consumption, and despite advice and counselling, continues to drink a bottle of wine a day. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vitals are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals ascites. His liver function tests are deranged. Transient elastography shows increased liver stiffness. Liver biopsy shows changes consistent with cirrhosis. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following are most likely to be seen on liver biopsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Macrovesicular steatosis and Mallory\u2019s hyaline","Deposition of granular material in peri-portal hepatocytes that is positive for Orcein","Bridging fibrosis between portal tracts","Lymphoid aggregates within portal tracts","Microvesicular steatosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe typical biopsy findings in alcohol-related liver disease are \u003Cstrong\u003Emacrovesicular steatosis \u003C/strong\u003Eand Mallory-Denk body, also known as Mallory body or \u003Cstrong\u003EMallory hyaline\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a deeply eosinophilic, ropy intracytoplasmic inclusion that represents aggregates of misfolded intermediate filaments with other different classes of proteins, including p62 and ubiquitin. Steatosis is defined as the accumulation of lipid droplets in the hepatocyte cytoplasm. Steatosis can be macrovesicular or microvesicular, depending not only on the size of the lipid droplet accumulated but also on the pathogenesis and etiology of the disease. When this progresses to become associated with inflammation, it is known as steatohepatitis. The pattern for macrovesicular steatosis in alcohol-related liver disease is typically centrilobular but it can progress to include the entire lobule in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther early changes seen in alcohol-related liver disease include the proliferation of smooth endoplasmic reticulum, distortion of mitochondria, and, if severe, can be associated with giant mitochondria. Giant mitochondria have been associated with all types of ALD from fatty liver to cirrhosis, and although they are not specific to ALD, the presence of giant mitochondria favours alcohol-related disease and is a good indicator of recent heaving drinking\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicrovesicular steatosis \u003C/strong\u003Eis rare and generally associated with either Reye\u0027s syndrome or acute fatty liver during pregnancy. It is a difficult finding to appreciate on H\u0026amp;E light microscopy and therefore, if suspected, should be confirmed/excluded with electron microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a necessary diagnostic feature of alcohol-related liver disease and will be seen in other (non-alcoholic) types of cirrhosis. Perivenular and pericellular (perisinusoidal) fibrosis is characteristic of fatty liver disease; as the disease progresses, portal / periportal fibrosis, bridging fibrosis, and cirrhosis may develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoid aggregates \u003C/strong\u003Eappear as slightly elevated nodules that may be normal in color or more red than the surrounding tissue. Sometimes they can look like small polyps. They can be seen in chronic hepatitis C as well as in autoimmune hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The typical biopsy findings in alcoholic liver disease are macrovesicular steatosis predominantly in the centrilobular zone and evidence of hepatocyte injury in the form of Mallory\u0027s hyaline, eosinophilic intracytoplasmic aggregates of cytokeratin filaments."],"references":["Torruellas C, French SW, Medici V. Diagnosis of alcoholic liver disease. World J Gastroenterol. 2014 Sep 7;20(33):11684-99."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35616"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","i